# Design Consistency Between Web and Mobile

When working on UI for this project, ensure web and mobile implementations match.

## Font Mapping

| Purpose | Web (Tailwind) | iOS (SwiftUI) |
|---------|----------------|---------------|
| Display/Title | `font-display` → Playfair Display | `.custom("Playfair Display", size: X)` |
| Body text | `font-body` → Crimson Pro | `.system(size: X, design: .serif)` |
| UI elements | `font-ui` → Inter | `.system(size: X, weight: .medium)` |

## Color Mapping (Stone Palette)

Both platforms use the stone color palette. On iOS, use the `Color.stoneXXX` extensions defined in `Theme.swift`.

| Color | Hex | Web Class | iOS |
|-------|-----|-----------|-----|
| stone-100 | #f5f5f4 | `text-stone-100` | `Color.stone100` |
| stone-400 | #a8a29e | `text-stone-400` | `Color.stone400` |
| stone-700 | #44403c | `bg-stone-700` | `Color.stone700` |
| stone-800 | #292524 | `bg-stone-800` | `Color.stone800` |

## Before Comparing Web vs Mobile

1. Verify web is using the correct font classes (`font-display`, `font-body`, `font-ui`)
2. Verify iOS is using the matching font configuration
3. Check that colors reference the same stone palette values

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- Using `font-serif` instead of `font-display` for titles (they're different!)
- Forgetting to register custom fonts in iOS Info.plist
- Mismatched spacing/padding values between platforms
